{
  "category": "categories2",
  "post_content": "<p><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-a949a9e3-7fff-9961-8ead-dc30ce9c48ae\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\">&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The tea ceremony, the way of tea, Teaism&mdash;there are equally numerous terms to refer to the practice in Japanese, highlighting the multifaceted nature of the traditional Japanese ritual of taking tea. One early term for the art is </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">chanoyu</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (茶の湯), literally meaning &ldquo;the hot water of tea,&rdquo; highlighting the refined aestheticism focused on the preparation, presentation, and enjoyment of the drink itself. The most precise term to refer to the ceremony itself would be </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">chaji</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (茶事 &ndash; tea event, matter of tea), calling to mind the formalized procedures of the ceremony and its role as a social gathering. Yet the most common term, and the most important in understanding the unique place of the tea ceremony in Japanese culture, is </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">sadou </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">(茶道 &ndash; the way of tea). The character </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">dou</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (道) can simply refer to a geographic &ldquo;way&rdquo; or &ldquo;path,&rdquo; but it is also often used in many philosophical contexts to refer to a much more fundamental &ldquo;way of life.&rdquo; </span></p>\n<p><strong style=\"font-weight: normal;\">&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">It is in understanding this sense of </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">sadou</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">&mdash;the importance of the way of tea in the Japanese way of life&mdash;that one understands the unique place it holds in traditional Japanese culture.</span></p>\n<p><strong style=\"font-weight: normal;\">&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The tea ceremony developed out of the blend of Buddhism and Taoism that is Japanese Zen, and at its heart lies a concern with purity and spiritual calm. Zen Buddhism seeks to find a window into spiritual transcendence, nirvana, in the Daoist effacement of the desiring self and unity with simple, natural experience. Rather than the ascetic practices of abusing the physical body or the mystic reliance on saintly teachers found in early Buddhism, Zen Buddhism focuses on finding inner calm through mindfulness of the self and of physical sensations in seated meditation. </span></p>\n<p><strong style=\"font-weight: normal;\">&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">This minimalist spirit of self-effacement and appreciation for natural simplicity is manifest in the tea ceremony. In a dedicated place of tranquility, the tea house, participants sit together in mindful peace, in turn sipping a drink of perhaps the most simple, natural drink humans have developed. The fragrant, earthy taste of the mix of leaf and water has been recognized as calming throughout the world. Zen Buddhists found in the peaceful ceremony dedicated to tea&rsquo;s appreciation a spiritual calm that actualized the ideals of natural harmony and mental purity sought in their practice.</span></p>\n<p><strong style=\"font-weight: normal;\">&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Behind the Leaves: A Short History</span></p>\n<p><strong style=\"font-weight: normal;\">&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Tea appreciation began in Japan as early as the 8</span><span style=\"font-size: 7.199999999999998pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: super; white-space: pre-wrap;\">th</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> century through tea leaves imported by ambassadors and traders from Tang-dynasty China (618-907). Japan truly made tea its own after monks such as Saicho (in 801) and Eisai (in 1191) brought back seeds of the tea plant and spread its harvest in gardens throughout Japan.</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"><img style=\"border: none; transform: rotate(0.00rad); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad);\" src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/V_DR2lSq_seyD69qzUeksluJxTsQpYHdevTuEUi35csEFeo1pNUFqzkQQEWI7TC_NSns0EJi9s36EkrTjEdHXl6qNAU8UyM4EBDB5NiDq-AEECu7cnZogScZ73MYAQFrxIvrYD9RpDBE0cgNgw\" width=\"624\" height=\"381\" /></span></p>\n<p><strong style=\"font-weight: normal;\">&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The tea ceremony proper finds its origins in a Zen Buddhist practice of taking tea before an image of the Buddha, a ritual cleansing of the mind that prepared monks for </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: underline; -webkit-text-decoration-skip: none; text-decoration-skip-ink: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">sessions of seated meditation</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (link to SEN Zazen article). In the Muromachi period (1336-1573), this practice was integrated into the intricate political world of feudal Japan: the ritual of taking tea was implemented between feudal lords negotiating a careful balance of power and alliances. The tea ceremony, in addition to its original Buddhist basis in spiritual cleansing, became seen as a mark of class and refinement, and schools of tea masters </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">[? </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: underline; -webkit-text-decoration-skip: none; text-decoration-skip-ink: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">such as Sen no Rikyu</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (link to SEN Rikyu article)]</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> formed to lead and instruct participants in proper practice.</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"><img style=\"border: none; transform: rotate(0.00rad); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad);\" src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/iLy4qql0tbxjxXa9EBf2eflIqGSM-3xYrN3SYfUXS5liSfrSeC9xC6vd86nZc2c4eBhyv4zuT6zxyiVNvveCtOuYMJCHN_5iK8h-TscOGis50P_qhBp9_1uKff7GNbHfTBJQd_KjgWgenTHiLw\" alt=\"File:TAIAN in MyokiAN Kyoto.jpg\" width=\"624\" height=\"441\" /></span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">teahouse of </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: underline; -webkit-text-decoration-skip: none; text-decoration-skip-ink: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Sen no Rikyu, the most famous master of the Japanese way of tea (link to Rikyu article?)</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The Practice </span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Types of Tea Ceremonies</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The tea ceremony can serve many distinct social functions, and the ceremonial procedures differ according to season and occasion. The most informal form is the o</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">yose no chakai </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">(大寄席の茶会 &ndash; tea gathering), a large-scale event in which a single host opens their halls or gardens to entertain a large number of guests. These are often seasonal events appreciating natural beauty: full moon viewings, </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: underline; -webkit-text-decoration-skip: none; text-decoration-skip-ink: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">flower viewings (link to SEN article on hanami)</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">&cedil; snow viewings, autumn leaf viewings. With large numbers and wide halls, the formal, personal exchange of tea takes a secondary role to the natural spectacle, giving the </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">oyose chakai </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">more of the excitement of a public festivity than the intimate serenity of the tea ceremony.</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The more formal performances of the tea ceremony are called </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">chaji </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">(茶事 &ndash; tea event). Though </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">chaji </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">can be held at other times of day to accommodate seasonal weather or the purposes of those gathering, the traditional </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">chaji </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">is a gathering centered at midday. As a formal event occurring between a small, specific group of people, throughout the ceremony the roles of host and guest are strictly divided.</span></p>\n<p><strong style=\"font-weight: normal;\">&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The Main Event: </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Chaji</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">chaji</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> begins with the invitation of guests,. The host sends out the invitation on formal </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">makigami</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (巻紙 &ndash; rolled letter paper), to which the guests respond in kind within 2-3 days to thank the host for the invitation and confirm their attendance. As the tea ceremony was intended to be performed in the tea room (link to tea house architecture article), the traditional tea ceremony is limited to serving 3-5 guests. The guest list is usually organized around a central figure &ndash; the head of a household, estate, or company &ndash; who handles most of the direct, ceremonial interactions between host and guests. </span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">When all the guests have arrived, they gather in the </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">roji</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (露地 &ndash; literally &ldquo;bare ground&rdquo;), the outdoor garden that serves as an antechamber to the teahouse, to await the host&rsquo;s summons. At the sounding of a bell or gong, the guests proceed to cleanse their hands and mouth at the </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">tsukubai</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (蹲 &ndash; literally, &ldquo;bending over,&rdquo; named for the process of bending down to wash), a stone basin in the tea garden. Thus purified, the participants then enter the tea room through a low crouching door. This short door is designed to direct the guests&rsquo; gaze towards the </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">tokonoma</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> alcove as they enter, allowing them to appreciate the hanging scroll and </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: underline; -webkit-text-decoration-skip: none; text-decoration-skip-ink: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">flowers arranged in traditional Japanese style</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (Link to SEN Ikebana article).</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"><img style=\"border: none; transform: rotate(0.00rad); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad);\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/owx35ojo7jeMfwanmyFqP6vPPFtXstb2a3XGHoWp5-YyL_63lJ2RiLnct6y5BDW22ftoG1XouR4pRF5iwuetJr9dnbNJplN8KKWpsLMNycBZmtZoTOO3Z6-CjL_CN15h_Yi1lxBFbxg94Hobww\" width=\"328\" height=\"361\" /></span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">　</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"><img style=\"border: none; transform: rotate(0.00rad); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad);\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/gA6-viLz9yvBRE8uKKVhdysI1mzO4e0ToJ9d9b6xEgnZsusOA2z1M1Pn9wXCSjZbWW8s9pS-A1V9fYOYjONa5m_jFY5tWTCIBj2cL-TRava449JK22RIP10o8phIIVdFYX0GW--7-az17dy7HQ\" width=\"272\" height=\"363\" /></span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">In the Altar of Tea</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The guests sit in a semi-circle around the central hearth, careful to leave an open space before the </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">tokonoma</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> alcove so that it remains in view to all participants. Seating locations indicate order of respect: the guest of honor sits closest to the </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">tokonoma</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">, and the prestige of each seat decreases as it moves farther from the alcove and closer to the entrance.</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"><img style=\"border: none; transform: rotate(0.00rad); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad);\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/1Ilt8XepulXS86uJtDjPOPCS2Ec72dIlPbH7mc0hQ62zk9so3wKHE7nnM1UdthGxoqL30Xjpi_cGsRslaD1_yzlzQvrm20BN6sZSpCkF2ujKzGLE_6vaZHAd2cZDGhXjORoNc6kn0F9fSCV87w\" alt=\"File:Tearoom layout.svg\" width=\"278\" height=\"285\" /></span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Thus seated, the guests are then treated to </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">kaiseki</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (懐石), a three-course meal served on a legless table. The first course of </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">kaiseki</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> generally consists of </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">sashimi</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">; the second course of steamed vegetables and tofu served in a clear broth; and the third of grilled fish. Bowls of rice and miso soup are served at the beginning of the meal and refilled by the host at each course. A cup of sake is served after the first and third courses, and once more following the meal alongside a pairing of delicacies from land and sea. The dining section of the service is finished off with </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: underline; -webkit-text-decoration-skip: none; text-decoration-skip-ink: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">a selection of traditional Japanese sweets, </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: underline; -webkit-text-decoration-skip: none; text-decoration-skip-ink: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">wagashi</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: underline; -webkit-text-decoration-skip: none; text-decoration-skip-ink: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (link to SEN Wagashi article).</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The guests then leave the room for a short recess. The host remains in the room and prepares for the central event of the tea ceremony, the serving of </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: underline; -webkit-text-decoration-skip: none; text-decoration-skip-ink: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">koicha</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: underline; -webkit-text-decoration-skip: none; text-decoration-skip-ink: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (濃茶), thick matcha green tea</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (link to SEN Matcha article). </span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The Main Event: </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Koicha</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"><img style=\"border: none; transform: rotate(0.00rad); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad);\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/KcE5wcxK14vpqkOWka8FGEsmUroAN5lYluJvcG4gzA6BMzSnJwlkjQj697NfawgoA7lnJx-Vi2kKpgfaNqMCooz8OVTPNC7HBusupirgus9_xOTKNG-aMXtTBMxj6EfmAE7ExAoZtc6nsDXaVA\" alt=\"File:Bamboo chasen to whisk koicha (15455038443).jpg\" width=\"579\" height=\"434\" /></span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">As before, the guests proceed the room at the summons of a gong. Once all are seated, the host demonstrates their cleansing of the </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">chadougu</span> <span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">(茶道具 &ndash; tea utensils) according to ceremonial procedure. Thick matcha-powder tea stirred by a bamboo whisk is then served in a single ceramic or lacquerware bowl, with the design on the rim facing the guest. After an exchange of bows between guest and host, the guest of honor takes a sip of the tea, rotating the cup to avoid drinking from the design, and passes it down the line to the next guest. The next guest, accepting the tea with another exchange of bows, repeats the procedure, until all guests have taken a drink from the tea cup. The cup is then passed back, and each guest admires it in turn before returning it to the host. Finally, the host once again cleanses the cup and </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">chadougu, </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">ending the most formal section of the ceremony.</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Letting off Steam: </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Usucha </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">and Closing the Ceremony</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.295; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 8pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The host then brings in leisure items, such as smoking sets, </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">higashi</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\"> (干菓子 &ndash; dried sweets), and cushions for the guests to enjoy during the casual </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: italic; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">usucha </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">(薄茶 &ndash; thin tea) portion of the ceremony. A cup of thin tea is provided to each guest, and once everything is set in place participants are now free to engage in more casual conversation. This is the opportunity for the participants to get to the business side of the meeting; depending on the occasion, this can mean cementing political relationships, discussing possible marriages, or simply relaxing and sharing recent family news.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">To bring the ceremony to a close, the host collects the used utensils and cleans them once more. The guest of honor formally requests to see the cleansed </span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; background-color: transparent; font-style: italic; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">chadougu</span><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; font-family: Verdana; background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">, and they are passed carefully for inspection in turn among the guests. The cups, whisks, and scoops are often handmade antiques or &nbsp;and their presentation is an opportunity for the host to display some of their most valued possessions.</span></p>",
  "title": "The Japanese Tea Ceremony",
  "meta_title": "The Japanese Tea Ceremony | Hotel Zen Tokyo Blog",
  "meta_description": "Tea appreciation began in Japan as early as the 8th century through tea leaves imported by ambassadors and traders from Tang-dynasty China (618-907). Japan truly made tea its own after monks such as Saicho (in 801) and Eisai (in 1191) brought back seeds of the tea plant and spread its harvest in gardens throughout Japan.",
  "url_friendly_name": "japanese-tea-ceremony",
  "date": "2018-10-16T15:00:00.000Z",
  "short_description": "The tea ceremony, the way of tea, Teaism—there are equally numerous terms to refer to the practice in Japanese, highlighting the multifaceted nature of the traditional Japanese ritual of taking tea. One early term for the art is chanoyu (茶の湯), literally meaning “the hot water of tea,” highlighting the refined aestheticism focused on the preparation, presentation, and enjoyment of the drink itself.",
